d; sizes 1 and 2 4\nks. Worth 25c. Spe- 15c 1\nby Caps; close-fitting styles; em- 4\nall sizes in the lot. Worth 24c 2\ns Dresses; embroidery and lace 1\n>rth $1.00 and $1.25. Spe- j\nJ\nlite Dresses; made of fine India 3\nnnes lace and embroidery, 3\nDresses; Russian and two- A for* 4\necial ttVC j\nWaists; made of cam- 1\n3 and 8 years. Worth 50c. 4\nen's .Corded Wash Hats/ large 3\nalso some embroidered j\n00. Special\n5 Seventh tSSa? j\nm I il Mf III\nK???n??{??n????????imi?Mimwni\nAn Ik\" fA i\n;ar Garments, 917 F St.\nlAMGAINSo\now ioo Strictly All-wool, New,\ndesirable styles, shades and macolored\neffects. Suits that were\n5.00 cut to\nand $15.\ng odds and ends of Garices:\nDr-made Suits; blues and blacks;\nfrom $21.00.\nh Coats; full satin-lined; sizes 36\no.\ns; one brown and two dark wine.\n\n5; light and dark colored effects.\nTwilled Cloth Coat; full box\nckets; satin lined. Were $10.00\n1 r\nC dUUVC 1LC1IIS 1U1 2\nS.OO,\nO. D. None exchanged,\nht Rustle Percaline Petticoats,\nRegular $2.00 quality. Special\nminnniniiiiniiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiimimimw\nducting: a handbook In various sections o\nthe city was filed today in the Pollc\n[ll Court against Ephrfam J. Hollis. thirty\ntiiree years old, proprietor of a lunch\nroom and commission merchant busines\nn at 206 10th street. At the Instance o\ncounsel far the defense the pleading va\nof postponed until heat Tuesday. Pendlni\n>ir the defendant's arraignment he Is at lib\n[e. erty under $T?0O cash bond.\nWarwick Institute Entertains.\nn g\nile A vaudeville entertainment was givei\nng last evening by members of the Warwicl\nict Athletic Institute, in Pythian Temple, be\nna fore a large audience. The program wa\na one of unusual merit. Following the per\nve formance dancing was in order. Thos\nhe who assisted in entertaining were A. F\nug Davidson. Juggler; Clark brothers, whit\ned tiers; B. Ermantraut, buck and wing dan\n>at cer: Charles A. Bright, baritone soloist\nnd Melburn the Mysterious, and the Metre\nhe politan quartet. The club officers are\nJohn Dugan, president; George J. Crosi\nvice president; John M. Smith, recordin,\nsecretary; Roland O. James, correspond\ning secretary, and Charles Fugltt, treat\n>n- urer.\n\nijCHANGE IN SENTIMEN\n?l .1\n\nr Opinions of New York Busi\n\nness Men Modified.\n\nLESS RANCOR EXHIBITE\nf\nNot So Much Hostility Toward tl\nPresident Shown.\nt ADMIT HIS GOOD INTENTION\nY\nY\nJ General Belief That Course of Chi\nl?\nExecutive Wonderfully Awakja\n\nened Business Conscience.\njs\njs\nBY WILLIAM F.. CURTIS.\nr Special Correspondence of The Star and 1\nChicago Record-Herald.\nNEW YORK, April 27. 190*\nA remarkable change has occurred\nthe sentiments as well as the mood\np the business men of New York concer\nf ing the President. The prejudice ai\nI hostility toward him have moderated in i\nextraordinary manner during the la\nfew weeks. The last time I was ov\nhere many prominent bankers, broke\nand others who spend much of their tin\nin Wall street were willing to assert th\nhe was insane, and an alienist of wi<\nreputation published an article in one\nthe most reputable magazines to pro?\nthat fact. Today the same men concei\nthat Roosevelt still retains his reason, b\nregre? that he is \"so impulsive and hea\nstrong\" and \"attempts to carry thin]\nwith a high hand.\" Everybody is willii\nto give him the credit of good intentior\nand, at the same time, they talk abo\nthe traditional \"bull in the china shop\nThey accuse him of vanity and unbecor\ning self-assertion.\nh The complaints against him, howevc\nhave become so modified that those w!\nhave held him entirely responsible for tl\nI financial losses t icy suffered in the pari\ni of last October are now willing to adrr\nj. that he was not so much to blame\nthey originally believed. They confe\nh that conditions in the financial and I\nh dustrial world were \"rotten.\" and th\nthings could not have gone on much Ion\nj* er without a crisis, which he provoki\nbefore its time; but in doing this, th<\nconcede, he undoubtedly prevented\nmuch more disastrous panic that wou\nprobably have occurred within a year\ntwo if it had ot been forced before\nwas ripe.\nBusiness Conscience Awakened.\nMany complaints are still bitter, b\nthey are qualified. \"He has treated i\nroughly, but it? has done us good.\" is\ncommon phrase. And another which 01\nhears on every hand is \"It wasn't wh\nhe did, but the way he did it,\" that ma<\nthe trouble. .\"When a man is sick y<\ncan't cure him by scaring him to death\n\"Skillful surgeons would not amputate\nlimb with a rtieat-ax, nor remove an i\ncer with a bayonet.\" Almost everybo<\nrecognizes that the President's policy\nattacking the corporations has result'\nin wholesome change of financial polii\nfor the benefit of their stockholders ai\nthe public, and has had a wonderful i\nfluence in awakening the business co\nscience of the country and elevating tl\nstandard of financial morals.\nOne of the most prominent busine\nmen of the country, who is familiar wi\nthe affairs and the methods of all t\ngreat captains of industry and financ\ntold me the otiher night that the rtan\nard of integrity in business methods hi\nbeen, gradually going ?own during t!\nh last ten years apd flj'at;' the Presidcnl\n\"ritlds on the corporations,\" as they a\ncalled, his exhortations |n his messag\nto Congress, his public\" speeches and 1\npublished correspondence had the sar\neffect as a religious revival in a church\n\"A feeling of distrust and a lack\nconfidence has been growing among t\npublic for several years,\" he said, \"ai\nparticularly among the managers, the c\nrectors, the stockholders of the lari\ncorporations in the .country. They ha\nseen so much of what Is called 'frenzi\nfinance.' Qf business trickery and di\nhonest competition, that they were b\nconning.hardened to it. Men of the hig\nest integrity winked at such things\ntreated them with indifference. The\nhas been an extraordinary change in tl\nrespect, however, since the panic and. e\nk though there has been no washing\ndirty linen on the streets, and t?he muc\nrakers are no more popular than tin\never were, the moral tone of the stre\nP Is higher, and he would be a bold mi\nwho attempted to repeat some of tl\ntransactions that have been tolerati\neven if they bave not been approve\nj among the men who control the flnanci\nand business worlds.\nConference of Steel Makers.\n\"As an illustration of this and as e\nexample of what may be done by r;\ntional methods and by mutual confident\nSnd co-operation I' can tell you a stoi\nf that has never been published or evi\nhinted at in print. It is especially si;\nnlflcant because it involves perhaps tl\nstrongest forces and the most effect!'\nmeans that have been exerted to resto\nconfidence, to prevent further flnanci\ndisturbances and revive industrial ai\ncommercial activity.\n\"Last October, in the midst of tl\npanic, in the period of greatest erne\ngency. Judge Elbert H. Gary, chairms\nof the board of directors of the ste\ntrust, summoned to New York fifty\nmore presidents and general manage\nof the iron and steel companies of tl\nUnited States, both those who are ind\npendent and the managers of the large\nbranches of the United States Steel Co\nporation. Gary described to them tl\ncritical situation and pointed out the di\nastrous consequences that would folio\nif public Confidence were not soon r\nstored and if the vast army of workmi\nthroughout the country were not ke\nbusy and paid their usual wages. He e\npressed the opinion that the key to tl\nsituation was in the hands of the iron ai\nsteel producers, and if they would mai\ntain prices and keep their men employe\nother manufacturers and industries ge\nerally would take confidence and folio\n?uft Ha nnlntpH out that thp iron nt\nsteel interests could much better afford\nlose a little money now than to lose\ngreat deal* within the next year or s\nthat It would be advisable for them\nsurrender their temporary profits ai\neven run behind for a time than to clo:\ndown entirely and demoralize the enti\nindustrial and commercial world. He b\nlleved they could prevent a general d\nmorallzatlon throughout the country\nthey would agree to stand together at\nshow a bold front and a firm conftdem\nIn the future, which, he believed, wou\nbe immediately reflected In the opinioi\nand transactions of every person wl\nused iron and steel.\na Proposed Friendly Agreement.\n\"Judge Gary explained that the lai\nf and public sentiment would not allow ai\ne formal contract or agreement to mginta\nprices or to divide territory or to all\nbusiness. On the other hand, the sen\nR rnent of the country was equally oppos\nf to hazardous competition that wou'.d\nfatal to many and injurious to all.\n5 proposed, therefore, an informal exchan\nof assurances among gentlemen that th\nwould maintain prifces; that they wot\nnot 'cut under' each other to secure bin\nness. and that fchey would help si.sta\nthe credit of each other and present\n1 united and confident front to the oth\nIt trades. Judge Gary gave such a pled\n_ in behalf of the United States Steel C<\nporatlon, which procruces w per cent\nthe tfon and steel In this country, a\ncan manufacture more cheaply than a\nof the other companies, because it mln\nits own coal and ore, produces all I\ni- own raw material, has Its own transpc\ni- tatlon lines and has spent more th;\n$400,000.<Nin in Improving Its equtpme\ni- and facilities for cheap production a\nr. marketing. He promised that It wot\ni. not take advantage of any of Us weak\ng independent competitors, but would a\nl- here strictly and under all circumstanc\nk to the price list that prevailed on trfe 1\nof October preceding the panic and woti\nf! FOR PIMPLES, TOO\nDiscovery Can* Oar tun ul\nEradlratn Minor Skla Tronblen\nj. Over MrM. j\nAbout a month the dispensers of poslam.\nthe new discovery for the rare of ecrema. decided\nto allow the druggist* of the country to\nhandle it. Previous to that time it could only be\nobtained direct from the laboratories.\nD Since this change in the method of dlstribn- I\ntion, poslatn has met with the most phenomenal\nsuccess of anything introduced to the drug trade\nIn the last thirty years. All leading druggists, j\nincluding ?(gram's and OTHrtmeU's. in Washing- 1\nton. are now carrying the special 50-cent slae\nrecently adopted, also the $2 Jsr.\nThis great success Is not surprising when It\nis remembered that, in erxema cases, poslam j\nstops the itching with first application, proceeds\nto heal immediately, and eures chronic cases In\na few weeks. Iin minor s^in troubles, such ss\npimples, blackheads, aene. herpes, blotches.\nrash. etc.. results show after au overnight appll- I\ncation. Experimental samples of poslam are\nsent to any one by mail free of .charge, by the\nEmergency Laboratories. 32 West 25th street.\nNew York city.\nnot underbid to secure contracts. Judge\nGary also announced that the steel corporation\nwas willing to furnish Its scale\nhe of prices to its competitors, tell them\nwhom it was dealing with and what its\nOMVS t asn /it n n an A r t /\\/I A/1 tf ?Sf Alll/1\nvuiiii avio nrc, yiuviuru cvci j uvuj nuutu\nin do the same.\n'If you helieve tihat it is a good plan\nor to get together and try to help each other\nn- instead of trying to injure each other,\nid and if the rest of you will make similar\nm pledges, the T'nited States \"Steel Corpora.\ntion will stand by these pledges indefs\ninitely.' said Judge Gary. Every man\ner present rose to his feet and gave assurrs\nanees quite as strong and definite as\nne those Judge Gary had given, and, after a\ngeneral exchange of views, it was agreed j\nthat there should lie frequent informal\nrtc meetings for consultation and that a\nof copimittee of seven sihouldTie appointed\nve to see that the pledges were carried out\nj and to give advice, information and assistance\nto members of the trade whenul\nevc$- it was needed, to hear complaints j\nd- about violations of the agreement, undue\nbs competition and unfair dealings gener-\nally. j\n\"The following gentlemen were apl8,\npointed on that committee:\nft \"E. h. Gary, chairman of the United\nStates $teel Corporation.\nn. \"Charles H. Schwab, Bethlehem Steel\nCompany.\n\"Powell Ptackhouse, Cambria Iron\n>r> Works. Johnstown.\n!io \"Willis L. King of Jones Laughlin,\nPittsburg.\n'*c \"E. C. Felt on. Pennsylvania Steel Companv.\nPhiladelphia. i\nas \"Edward Bailey. Central Iron Comss\npany. Harrisburg.\nn\" \"W. E. Corey, president United States\nat Steel Corporation. i\nged\nOperation of the Agreement.\ne>' \"This committee was organized in No-\nvember and held repeated meetings, some\nor of them being attended by other influenit\ntial men in the trade. It has worked with\nperfect harmony and has brought about a\nfriendly relationship among the manu-\nfacturers of iron and steel in this country\nwhich was never approached by any\nus trade orcranization that ever existed be\na fore. The most perfect confidence exists\nne between rival establishments; they exat\nchange information concerning contracts,\ncost of materials, cost of production,\nwage scales and other matters as freely\nas if all were members of the same firm.\nThe committee has heard several coma\nplaints, but none of them have been seri'\nous. Nearly all of them have been with!y\nout foundation.\n\"Not long ago the manager of an inde_\npendent company came to the committee\npy to complain that one of his competitors\n1(1 who had been present at the October\nn\" 'meeting and had given the same a^surn\"\nanees as the rest, by cutting prices, had\ntie beaten him out of a large contract, to\nwhich he was clearly entitled. The memb\"rs\nof the committee\" questioned him\nth closely and got all the Information he\n,ie had. Then they requested him to keep\nthe matter entirely secret until they were\ngiven ar. opportunity to look into the\n*d other side of the case, which they did.\n[1? They found, to their gratification, that\n1 s there had bpen no price cutting; that the\nre bids were almost precisely similar, but\nthe man making the complaint had lost\nlls the contract because his competitor\nne agreed to finish the Job in a shorter time.\nWhen these facts were laid before him\nhe admitted he was wrong and is mow\nperfectly satisfied.\nJ1\" \"In another instance a complaint was\nmade that the manager of one of the\nse auxiliary companies of the Steel Trust\nhad been evading the'agreement. An investigation\nshowed that he had plainly\ns\" exposed himself to such a suspicion, although\nhis action was susceptible of two\nconstructions. He was called before th6\nor committee and the matter was explained\nre by him. While he was not willing to adlis\nmit that he was wrong, he acknowledged\ni*- that the other man had grounds for doubt\nof and readily agreed to revise the trans\nk- action so that there should not be any\npy question of his motives or his acts.\nHigh Standard Maintained.\nhe \"Theso two illustrations sjiow how\npd carefully the managers of the iron and i\nsteel Interests are maintaining the high\na standard of business morality they have\nfixed for themselves, and since their or- {j\nganizatlon the leading men in several\nin other lines of business are getting toa\nget her for the same purpose. 'iue con- _\nce certed action of the iron, and steel peo-\nl.. pie has also had a powerful influence in\nrestoring confidence, in keeping tne\nwheels in motion, and in preventing furs'\nther financial disturbances.\nie \"The same gentlemen who v.ere called\n,,p together by Judge Gary in October had a c,\nreunion after an experience of six t,\nr<: months. He gave them a dinner at the\na Waldorf-Astoria at which congnatula- s\nld tions were exchanged, assurances were P\nrenewed, and the leading manufacturers w\nie gave their views ?mcerning present anu ti\nr\" future conditions. They were unanimobs\nin In their opinion that the previous pros- 11\nel perity would soon he recovered; that the it\n\"r business outlook in every direction was v\nrs encouraging, and that it would not be s]\nlie long before the large army of unemployed\ne- would he again at work. It was surprisst\ning and gratifying to observe the feelings t<\nr- of friendship and confia^nce which now b\nhe exist among those who were formerly p\na- ugly and often hitter rivals in business.\"\nw\ne* OUTING AT CLOVES SHORE. a,\n?n ti\nx- Party From This City Guests of\n1'j Thomas F. McNulty. h\nn- Thomas F. McNulty of Baltimore, who c\npd has many friends in this city, entertained y\nn\" a party at Clover shore, Bear creek, near P\nBaltimore, yesterday. The shore dinner\nto prepared by the host included meats of all lt\na kinds and was greatly enjoyed by the A\nguests who had participated In games on n\nthe shore. Mayor Stoy of Atlantic. City a\nse was to have been a guest, but he was\nre summoned home yesterday morning. jj\ne* Among those from this city who enjoyed\nthe outing were J. W. Cummings, ci\nul Henry I. &uinn. Florence A. Sullivan, \\V.\nce A. Carson. John H. Miller, M. P. Sulli-\nId van. Frank P. Madigan, T. Howard\nis Brooks. Frederick W. Miller, John J. Aliu\nlen, Roger Williams. R. C. Johnson,\nCharles Crawford, William Stockman and\nC. G. Johnson.\nThe Baltlmoreans in the party were M\nvs Messrs. J^mes Guyton. James King, P. E\nnv H. King, Thomas H. Hamilton, James E. p\nHamilton. John Patrick Nixon, W. J. Mc-\nGraw, John H. Hall, Henry Mears, Felix A\nlot Bannon. James M. Wilson. Edward Grati\nham. Thomas McDonald, J. E. Dorn and H\ned Samuel Greenwald. sr.\nJames H. J. McNally and James E.\nMurphy of Philadelphia were also among s\nd? the guests. B\nso In welcoming the guests to Clover shore si\ney Mr. McNulty referred to his many pleas- B\nild ant associations In this city, touching m\nsi- upon the growth and improvements that B\ntin had been made since his first visit here B\na and predicted that Washtngtoh and Baiter\ntlmorp will some day be one city. M\nge M. P. Su